  <p>Selling a house "as-is" sounds straightforward, but there's a lot of confusion about what it actually means, who buys as-is properties, and whether you'll end up leaving money on the table. This guide answers those questions honestly.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>💡 <strong>The short version:</strong> "As-is" means you're not making any repairs before the sale. You can list as-is with a Realtor or sell directly to a cash buyer. The strategies are very different and the right one depends on your situation.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>What "As-Is" Actually Means</h2>
  <p>When you sell a property as-is, you're communicating that what buyers see is what they get. You won't be doing repairs before closing. You're not hiding defects — Kansas requires disclosure of known material defects — but you're not fixing them either.</p>
  <p>This can apply to a house that needs minor cosmetic work all the way up to a property with major structural issues. "As-is" isn't a condition level — it's a sales approach.</p>

  <h2>Option 1: List As-Is With a Realtor</h2>
  <p>You can list an as-is property on the MLS. The upside is exposure to a wide pool of buyers. The downside is that many financed buyers (FHA, VA loans) can't purchase properties with certain condition issues — their loans require the home to meet minimum property standards.</p>
  <p>As-is listings also tend to attract lowball offers from investors, and you'll still pay 5–6% commission. This route works best for homes in average condition that just need some updates — not properties with significant repairs needed.</p>

  <h2>Option 2: Sell Directly to a Cash Buyer</h2>
  <p>Cash buyers purchase as-is properties specifically. No financing contingencies, no inspections that can kill a deal, no demands for repairs before closing. The offer will be below retail market value — but there are no commissions, no repair costs, and typically no closing costs.</p>

  <h2>How Cash Offers Are Calculated</h2>
  <p>Here's the basic math a cash buyer uses — and why we show our work:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>After Repair Value (ARV)</strong> — what the property is worth once fully renovated</li>
    <li><strong>Estimated repair costs</strong> — based on what we actually see</li>
    <li><strong>Holding costs</strong> — taxes, insurance, utilities during renovation</li>
    <li><strong>Selling costs</strong> — commission and closing when we eventually sell</li>
    <li><strong>Profit margin</strong> — what makes the project viable for us</li>
  </ul>
  <p>What's left after subtracting all of that is what we can offer you. It's not arbitrary — and if you ask us to explain it, we will.</p>

  <h2>When Selling As-Is to a Cash Buyer Makes Sense</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The property needs significant repairs you can't afford or don't want to manage</li>
    <li>You need to sell quickly — 7 to 30 days vs. 60 to 90+ days on market</li>
    <li>You're dealing with a complicated situation (inherited property, divorce, foreclosure)</li>
    <li>You don't want strangers walking through during open houses</li>
    <li>You want certainty — no deals falling through due to financing</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When It Might Not Be the Right Move</h2>
  <p>If your house is in good condition and you have 60–90 days, listing with a Realtor will almost certainly net you more money. The cash buyer route trades price for speed and certainty. That trade-off is worth it for a lot of people — and not worth it for others. We'll always give you an honest read.</p>

